==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Steen
<hw>Steen</hw> <pr>(st⟦emac⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>st⟦aemac⟧na</ets>. See <er>Stone</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>stean</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A vessel of clay or
stone.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An huge great earth-pot <xex>steane</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A wall of brick, stone, or cement, used as a lining,
as of a well, cistern, etc.; a steening.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Steen
<hw>Steen</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>st⟦aemac⟧nan</ets> to
adorn with stones or gems. See <er>Stone</er>.]</ety> <def>To line, as a
well, with brick, stone, or other hard material.</def> <altsp>[Written
also <asp>stean</asp>, and <asp>stein</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steenbok</ent>⟦br⟧
